JIMMY:
So can I, uh, tell Howard...

53
00:05:59,734 --> 00:06:03,488
...you're not quitting,
or retiring or whatever?

54
00:06:04,447 --> 00:06:07,992
And can we take all this shit
down off the walls?

55
00:06:10,661 --> 00:06:12,789
I'm gonna go call Howard.

56
00:06:12,955 --> 00:06:14,290
CHUCK:
Jimmy.

57
00:06:14,457 --> 00:06:18,711
You do realize you just confessed
to a felony?

58
00:06:18,961 --> 00:06:20,630
JIMMY:
I guess.

59
00:06:20,797 --> 00:06:23,049
But you feel better, right?

60
00:06:23,674 --> 00:06:26,636
Besides, it's your word against mine.

61
00:06:46,989 --> 00:06:48,491
[DOOR CLOSES]

62
00:07:01,879 --> 00:07:03,589
[CHUCK SHUDDERS]

63
00:07:09,303 --> 00:07:10,555
JIMMY:
<i>Absolutely.</i>

64
00:07:10,721 --> 00:07:12,515
Coming back.

65
00:07:13,015 --> 00:07:14,851
What's it matter what I said, Howard?

66
00:07:15,017 --> 00:07:18,187
Why are you looking a gift horse
in the mouth? He just--

67
00:07:18,896 --> 00:07:21,524
Yeah. Well, whatever it was,
he's over it now. All right?

68
00:07:21,816 --> 00:07:24,652
And by the way, you're welcome.

69
00:07:34,620 --> 00:07:38,624
Well, Howard's breathing again.
You made him very happy.

70
00:08:06,611 --> 00:08:07,987
Jimmy.

71
00:08:08,154 --> 00:08:09,947
Jimmy, if you're gonna help...

72
00:08:10,114 --> 00:08:12,158
...at least use a little finesse, won't you?

73
00:08:12,325 --> 00:08:15,119
-Finesse? What do you--?
-Quit yanking at it. You're--

74
00:08:15,286 --> 00:08:17,997
You're pulling the varnish
right off the walnut.

75
00:08:18,164 --> 00:08:22,960
-I'm not pulling any varnish off the walnut.
-You most certainly are. Look. Look. See?

76
00:08:23,127 --> 00:08:25,379
Maybe you should've thought
about the walnut...

77
00:08:25,546 --> 00:08:28,508
-...before you covered it in duct tape.
-I don't need your help.

78
00:08:28,674 --> 00:08:32,637
-I don't recall ever asking for it.
-I'm sorry. Okay?

79
00:08:32,887 --> 00:08:35,640
Finesse. Fine. Show me. Demonstrate.

80
00:08:35,806 --> 00:08:37,517
Like this.

81
00:08:38,142 --> 00:08:42,563
Gently roll it with your thumbs.

82
00:08:42,730 --> 00:08:45,483
Left and then right.

83
00:08:45,650 --> 00:08:48,069
You see? Alternate the thumbs.

84
00:08:48,236 --> 00:08:50,488
Up and down.

85
00:08:50,780 --> 00:08:53,574
Ahem. Get a nice tight roll going.

86
00:08:53,741 --> 00:08:57,203
Sorry. I think you're the one
that needs a nice tight roll.

87
00:08:57,787 --> 00:08:59,872
Come on. Show me.

88
00:09:00,456 --> 00:09:02,291
Gently. Gently.

89
00:09:02,458 --> 00:09:04,043
Left, then right.

90
00:09:04,585 --> 00:09:05,586
Left, right.

91
00:09:05,753 --> 00:09:08,548
I get it. Wax on, wax off.

92
00:09:08,839 --> 00:09:11,008
Mr. Miyagi.

93
00:09:11,300 --> 00:09:13,052
<i>Karate Kid.</i>

94
00:09:15,888 --> 00:09:17,765
Seriously?

95
00:09:30,069 --> 00:09:31,904
Oh, my God.

96
00:09:32,071 --> 00:09:35,116
<i>The Adventures of Mabel.</i> I--

97
00:09:35,283 --> 00:09:37,785
I haven't thought about this in forever.
Remember this?

98
00:09:37,952 --> 00:09:39,662
I do.

99
00:09:40,204 --> 00:09:42,456
-Harry Thurston Peck.
-Yeah.

100
00:09:42,623 --> 00:09:44,667
Mabel goes into the mountain...

101
00:09:44,834 --> 00:09:48,379
...and she meets the king of the brownies,
and he gives her...

102
00:09:48,546 --> 00:09:51,966
...some kind of super-delicious jelly, and--

103
00:09:53,092 --> 00:09:55,094
Holy crap. 1912.

104
00:09:55,261 --> 00:09:57,513
Yeah. Belonged to Grammy Davenport.

105
00:09:57,680 --> 00:09:59,181
She wrote her name in it.

106
00:09:59,348 --> 00:10:03,811
She was reading that to her school kids
the year the <i>Titanic</i> went down.

107
00:10:03,978 --> 00:10:04,979
Damn.

108
00:10:05,146 --> 00:10:06,731
Then Mom read it to me.

109
00:10:06,897 --> 00:10:09,483
I read it to you.

110
00:10:10,985 --> 00:10:12,028
You don't remember.

111
00:10:12,194 --> 00:10:13,696
Yeah. Yeah.

112
00:10:13,863 --> 00:10:16,198
I do now that you say it. Yeah.

113
00:10:16,365 --> 00:10:19,493
What was I, like 5 or 6?

114
00:10:20,244 --> 00:10:22,079
You had had...

115
00:10:22,246 --> 00:10:27,126
...this weird nightlight
that you were so crazy about.

116
00:10:27,293 --> 00:10:28,919
It was, um--

117
00:10:29,420 --> 00:10:30,421
It was Daffy Duck.

118
00:10:30,588 --> 00:10:33,174
It was some Daffy Duck rip-off
with this weird red bill.

119
00:10:33,341 --> 00:10:34,884
-Mouth. Oh, yeah. The bill.
-Yeah.

120
00:10:35,051 --> 00:10:37,887
It used to get so hot,
we thought it'd burn the house down...

121
00:10:38,054 --> 00:10:41,515
-...but you wouldn't let anybody touch it.
-Honest to--

122
00:10:41,682 --> 00:10:43,976
You got a great memory, Chuck.

123
00:10:44,143 --> 00:10:46,937
That red bill and everything. Hey.

124
00:10:47,104 --> 00:10:51,317
What was the name of that little girl
that lived three houses up from us?

125
00:10:51,484 --> 00:10:53,778
-She had, like, a pageboy haircut...
-Jimmy.

126
00:10:53,944 --> 00:10:56,572
...and she was always in the dirt,
always dirty.

127
00:10:56,739 --> 00:10:59,367
-I liked her, and she was always--
-Jimmy. Jimmy.

128
00:11:00,660 --> 00:11:03,788
Don't think I'll ever forget
what happened here today.

129
00:11:10,961 --> 00:11:13,172
And you will pay.

130
00:11:31,107 --> 00:11:33,901
You didn't mention my garden.

131
00:11:34,068 --> 00:11:35,903
Your garden is part of your backyard...

132
00:11:36,070 --> 00:11:38,614
...so it's included in the property
that goes to Jenn.

133
00:11:38,781 --> 00:11:41,492
It comes with the house, Mom.

134
00:11:41,659 --> 00:11:44,370
Well, I think you need
to mention it by name...

135
00:11:44,537 --> 00:11:48,416
...in case some dirty judge
decides to play tricks.

136
00:11:48,916 --> 00:11:52,086
Okay. We can do that.

137
00:11:53,045 --> 00:11:54,672
Let's see.

138
00:11:55,214 --> 00:11:57,049
Garden.

139
00:11:57,216 --> 00:11:59,260
Hey, I'm back. Oh, hi, ladies. Jimmy McGill.

140
00:11:59,427 --> 00:12:01,220
Hey, Jimmy. We are almost done here.

141
00:12:01,637 --> 00:12:03,722
-Great. Can I--?
-We're almost done.

142
00:12:03,889 --> 00:12:06,183
I'll be with you in a minute.

143
00:12:13,023 --> 00:12:14,233
Oh.

144
00:12:14,400 --> 00:12:16,110
And mention my lily pond.

145
00:12:16,277 --> 00:12:18,320
It's in my garden.

146
00:12:19,530 --> 00:12:21,157
Lily pond.

147
00:12:33,961 --> 00:12:36,464
KIM: Okay, ladies.
JENN: Thanks so much for your help.

148
00:12:36,630 --> 00:12:39,008
KIM: You're very welcome.
Thank you for being so patient.

149
00:12:39,175 --> 00:12:42,178
And, Mrs. Aherne, if you or Margaret
ever need anything from me...

150
00:12:42,344 --> 00:12:44,597
...anything at all,
you can call me day or night.

151
00:12:44,763 --> 00:12:46,807
This is Mrs. Siemasko and her daughter Jenn.

152
00:12:46,974 --> 00:12:49,685
I'm sorry.
I get my wires crossed a little.

153
00:12:49,852 --> 00:12:51,020
-Bye.
MRS. SIEMASKO: Bye.

154
00:12:51,187 --> 00:12:52,229
-Drive safe.
JENN: Thank you.

155
00:12:52,396 --> 00:12:54,106
Okay. Thank you.

156
00:12:56,275 --> 00:12:57,902
You are a superhero.

157
00:12:58,068 --> 00:13:00,946
I owe you big time.

158
00:13:09,371 --> 00:13:10,873
Huh.

159
00:13:11,749 --> 00:13:13,417
So how's Chuck?

160
00:13:13,584 --> 00:13:16,837
Crisis averted, I guess. I mean...

161
00:13:17,004 --> 00:13:20,883
...he's back to being
the same old Chuck, so....

162
00:13:21,425 --> 00:13:23,427
Wanna talk about it?

163
00:13:24,011 --> 00:13:25,554
Depends.

164
00:13:25,721 --> 00:13:27,473
It may or may not involve...

165
00:13:27,640 --> 00:13:30,267
...that thing you said you never,
ever wanted to discuss.

166
00:13:30,434 --> 00:13:32,770
Okay. Then thanks.

167
00:13:32,937 --> 00:13:34,230
I gotta get back to it.

168
00:13:34,396 --> 00:13:38,108
How about we call it a day?
I'll buy you some dinner.

169
00:13:38,275 --> 00:13:39,276
You're kidding, right?

170
00:13:39,443 --> 00:13:41,237
You realize how far behind I am...

171
00:13:41,403 --> 00:13:43,906
...not to mention,
now I've got eight wills to finish?

172
00:13:44,073 --> 00:13:45,366
What? I'll do the wills.

173
00:13:45,533 --> 00:13:47,201
-No, you won't.
-Of course I will...

174
00:13:47,368 --> 00:13:49,036
...do the wills. They're my clients.

175
00:13:49,203 --> 00:13:51,789
They're my clients.
You and I aren't partners, remember?

176
00:13:51,956 --> 00:13:54,667
Once I take people on,
I can't just reassign them to you.

177
00:13:54,833 --> 00:13:57,461
Oh, come on. Why you getting all,
like, legal on me, huh?

178
00:13:57,628 --> 00:13:59,338
Who cares?

179
00:14:00,005 --> 00:14:03,759
I told every single one the situation:
that they'd be getting me instead of you.

180
00:14:03,926 --> 00:14:06,011
I tried to talk them into coming another day.

181
00:14:06,178 --> 00:14:08,180
Six left. Maybe you'll get those back.

182
00:14:08,347 --> 00:14:11,183
-Look. If this is about the money--
-It's not about the money.

183
00:14:11,350 --> 00:14:12,810
You can keep the money.

184
00:14:12,977 --> 00:14:14,895
Don't act like I wanted this.

185
00:14:15,062 --> 00:14:17,565
Jesus, like I need more on my plate?

186
00:14:24,238 --> 00:14:25,865
Are you mad?

187
00:14:27,616 --> 00:14:29,451
I'm not mad.

188
00:14:31,078 --> 00:14:32,705
I'm just, uh...

189
00:14:35,082 --> 00:14:37,376
...thinking about things.

190
00:14:43,465 --> 00:14:46,886
For 10 minutes today, Chuck didn't hate me.

191
00:14:49,388 --> 00:14:51,807
I forgot what that felt like.

192
00:15:17,499 --> 00:15:18,834
CHUCK [OVER RECORDER]:
<i>Jimmy.</i>

193
00:15:20,336 --> 00:15:24,506
<i>You do realize</i>
<i>you just confessed to a felony?</i>

194
00:15:25,007 --> 00:15:26,759
JIMMY:
<i>I guess.</i>

195
00:15:26,926 --> 00:15:29,136
<i>But you feel better, right?</i>

196
00:15:30,137 --> 00:15:33,223
<i>Besides, it's your word against mine.</i>

197
00:15:33,557 --> 00:15:35,434
CHUCK:
That's the end of it.

198
00:15:36,936 --> 00:15:38,395
Howard.

199
00:15:38,562 --> 00:15:40,064
-That's the end.
-Mm.

200
00:15:40,397 --> 00:15:41,732
[SWITCHES OFF RECORDER]

201
00:15:42,066 --> 00:15:43,442
Could you...?

202
00:15:44,109 --> 00:15:45,861
Oh. Yeah.

203
00:15:49,490 --> 00:15:52,368
Well, now do you believe me?

204
00:15:55,329 --> 00:15:57,748
I don't even know where to begin.

205
00:15:58,374 --> 00:15:59,750
But yes, I believe you.

206
00:16:01,293 --> 00:16:04,088
Your brother is one
world-class son of a bitch.

207
00:16:05,381 --> 00:16:06,548
No offense.

208
00:16:07,967 --> 00:16:11,428
I just really wish you'd told me
about these plans of yours...

209
00:16:11,595 --> 00:16:15,432
-...before you went out and did it.
-I know, Howard, and I regret misleading you.

210
00:16:15,599 --> 00:16:19,687
It's just that a certain vérité
had to be established.

211
00:16:19,853 --> 00:16:22,982
I'm not talking about the heart attack
that you nearly gave me.

212
00:16:23,524 --> 00:16:25,442
Chuck, this tape.

213
00:16:25,609 --> 00:16:28,195
I'm not sure exactly what it accomplishes.

214
00:16:28,362 --> 00:16:30,531
You know evidentiary rules
better than I do...

215
00:16:30,698 --> 00:16:34,535
...but a secretly recorded tape
with a problematic chain of evidence?

216
00:16:34,618 --> 00:16:36,578
Gonna have a hell of a time
getting that admitted.

217
00:16:36,662 --> 00:16:39,373
-I agree.
-And if you put it in front of a jury...

218
00:16:39,540 --> 00:16:43,669
...Jimmy'd call a dozen audio experts to say
that voice isn't his, tape had been edited.

219
00:16:43,836 --> 00:16:44,837
He would, indeed.

220
00:16:45,004 --> 00:16:48,173
Are you thinking about playing this
for Kevin Wachtell at Mesa Verde?

221
00:16:48,340 --> 00:16:51,802
Because as much as I would love to,
that ship has sailed.

222
00:16:51,969 --> 00:16:53,929
We're never getting them back, regardless.

223
00:16:54,096 --> 00:16:57,016
Oh, I doubt we could even
get in the door over there.

224
00:16:57,182 --> 00:17:01,228
If that tape is useless in a court of law
and no help in the court of public opinion...

225
00:17:01,395 --> 00:17:02,563
...what's the point?

226
00:17:02,730 --> 00:17:05,190
Because I can't think of a single use for it.

227
00:17:06,525 --> 00:17:08,193
I can.

228
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:14,700
[CAR HORN BLARING]

229
00:17:18,537 --> 00:17:20,539
[♪♪♪]

230
00:18:51,296 --> 00:18:53,590
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

231
00:19:14,736 --> 00:19:16,905
[♪♪♪]

232
00:21:55,022 --> 00:21:56,690
Hey, mister.

233
00:21:56,857 --> 00:21:59,943
We're closing in 15 minutes.

234
00:22:02,487 --> 00:22:03,697
[SCOFFS]

235
00:22:06,533 --> 00:22:08,827
Call me a cab, will you?

236
00:22:11,246 --> 00:22:13,332
What about your vehicle?

237
00:22:14,166 --> 00:22:15,959
Keep it.

238
00:22:20,255 --> 00:22:22,299
MAN:
Five J's Auto Salvage.

239
00:22:22,966 --> 00:22:25,969
Broadway, at Bobby Foster's.

240
00:22:26,762 --> 00:22:29,264
Yeah. Ehr-- Ehr-- Ehr--

241
00:22:29,431 --> 00:22:30,682
How is it again?

242
00:22:30,849 --> 00:22:32,559
Ehrmantraut.

243
00:22:32,726 --> 00:22:34,978
Yeah. Ehrmantraut.

244
00:22:35,395 --> 00:22:36,855
Yeah.

245
00:22:37,147 --> 00:22:40,567
Just tell him to pull up
to the gate and honk.

246
00:22:41,193 --> 00:22:42,235
Okay.

247
00:22:42,402 --> 00:22:43,987
Thanks.

248
00:22:44,154 --> 00:22:45,363
They're on their way.

249
00:22:45,530 --> 00:22:47,240
Thank you.

250
00:23:10,430 --> 00:23:13,767
[TSKS THEN GROANS]

251
00:23:34,704 --> 00:23:38,291
Do you sell a gas cap
for an '87 Caprice wagon?

252
00:23:38,458 --> 00:23:43,046
Should. GM cap should be the blue
on the bottom there.

253
00:23:52,973 --> 00:23:55,684
[♪♪♪]

254
00:26:50,525 --> 00:26:53,403
You're sure I can't help carry those
to your car, Mrs. Vankamp?

255
00:26:53,570 --> 00:26:54,696
Don't be a silly.

256
00:26:54,863 --> 00:26:58,408
I only hope I didn't take too much
of your time with all my dusty old photos.

257
00:26:58,575 --> 00:27:02,454
Goodness, no.
Your grandson's wedding was gorgeous.

258
00:27:02,620 --> 00:27:05,457
When I come back,
I'll show you my niece's confirmation.

259
00:27:05,623 --> 00:27:08,001
-Wait till you see the flowers.
-Oh!

260
00:27:08,168 --> 00:27:10,920
-Roses, petunias, orchids.
-Uh-huh. Yes.

261
00:27:11,087 --> 00:27:13,631
-They don't smell, you know. Baby's breath.
-Well--

262
00:27:13,798 --> 00:27:16,760
-And bachelor buttons. Lilies of the valley.
-Okay.

263
00:27:16,926 --> 00:27:20,013
-Well, I'll believe it when I see it.
-Daisies. Daisies don't tell.

264
00:27:20,180 --> 00:27:22,599
Now I've got something to look forward to.
Okay, bye.

265
00:27:22,766 --> 00:27:24,976
-Bye.
-See you.

266
00:27:26,227 --> 00:27:27,354
[SIGHS]

267
00:27:27,520 --> 00:27:31,566
Thank you for waiting so patiently.
Who do we have next?

268
00:27:34,944 --> 00:27:36,571
That'd be me.

269
00:27:41,993 --> 00:27:43,536
Hello, hello.

270
00:27:43,703 --> 00:27:45,205
It's so good to see you again.

271
00:27:45,747 --> 00:27:50,168
I escorted you and your clients onto my base.

272
00:27:50,335 --> 00:27:52,712
I treated you with hospitality and respect.

273
00:27:52,879 --> 00:27:55,715
Now I come to find every word
out of your mouth is a damn lie.

274
00:27:55,882 --> 00:27:58,301
Captain, please, sit down, take a load off.

275
00:27:58,468 --> 00:28:01,304
Hey, I'll get you a complimentary coffee,
or a soft drink?

276
00:28:01,471 --> 00:28:04,057
And your so-called war hero, "Fudge" Talbot?

277
00:28:04,224 --> 00:28:06,101
No such person. Never was.

278
00:28:06,267 --> 00:28:09,187
Granted, some artistic license
may have been taken.

279
00:28:09,354 --> 00:28:12,107
You entered government property
under false pretenses, sir.

280
00:28:12,273 --> 00:28:15,110
I am no expert on your procedures
and protocols and whatnot...

281
00:28:15,276 --> 00:28:17,654
...so if we failed to cross a T
or dot an I...

282
00:28:17,737 --> 00:28:20,407
...I sincerely apologize
for any misunderstanding.

283
00:28:20,573 --> 00:28:23,493
-No, it's not a misunderstanding.
-Step back. Big picture this.

284
00:28:23,660 --> 00:28:24,786
What damage was done?

285
00:28:24,953 --> 00:28:26,746
Hey, who was hurt, huh?

286
00:28:26,913 --> 00:28:29,332
What was damaged?
The base is still there, right?

287
00:28:29,499 --> 00:28:31,626
-The B-52 is, I presume, still--?
-B-29.

288
00:28:31,793 --> 00:28:35,046
-Huh?
-B-29. <i>Fifi's</i> a B-29.

289
00:28:36,172 --> 00:28:37,549
[CHUCKLES]

290
00:28:37,924 --> 00:28:40,760
Oh, this is all just
one big joke to you. Huh?

291
00:28:41,511 --> 00:28:43,346
-You don't like the commercial.
-I don't.

292
00:28:43,513 --> 00:28:46,516
-But this has nothing to do--
-Constructive criticism is welcome.

293
00:28:46,683 --> 00:28:49,728
But you should realize
that most people find it uplifting.

294
00:28:49,894 --> 00:28:50,895
Patriotic, even.

295
00:28:51,062 --> 00:28:53,565
Check recruiting numbers.
I think you'll see an uptick.

296
00:28:53,732 --> 00:28:56,693
And you know what?
If it turns out Fudge wasn't in the war--

297
00:28:56,860 --> 00:28:59,279
Fudge is not a person. He wasn't in the war.

298
00:28:59,446 --> 00:29:02,991
Well, neither was Tom Cruise,
and look what <i>Top Gun</i> did for you.

299
00:29:03,825 --> 00:29:05,034
You lied to me.

300
00:29:05,201 --> 00:29:08,037
You lied to my face,
and I can't let you get away with it.

301
00:29:08,830 --> 00:29:11,666
I think we just--
We're just gonna have to agree to disagree.

302
00:29:11,833 --> 00:29:14,169
So can I get you that coffee to go, or--?

303
00:29:14,335 --> 00:29:17,881
No, no, I'm gonna tell you
what's happening now.

304
00:29:18,047 --> 00:29:19,883
You're gonna take that ad off the air.

305
00:29:20,049 --> 00:29:24,179
And if you play it one more time, I'll go to
the judge advocate, and we'll take you down.

306
00:29:24,345 --> 00:29:27,891
Trespassing, false representation,
stolen valor, the whole nine yards.

307
00:29:28,057 --> 00:29:29,768
For eight seconds of a TV commercial?

308
00:29:29,934 --> 00:29:33,772
You take that ad down,
or there'll be hell to pay.

309
00:29:33,938 --> 00:29:35,774
That clear enough for you?

310
00:29:37,942 --> 00:29:38,985
Make me.

311
00:29:39,736 --> 00:29:41,654
-Yeah? Make you?
-Heh. Yeah.

312
00:29:41,821 --> 00:29:43,865
Let's do this. Bring your commander here.

313
00:29:44,032 --> 00:29:46,910
I'll explain how you let us on the base,
red-carpet treatment--

314
00:29:47,076 --> 00:29:48,787
Because you lied your way in.

315
00:29:48,953 --> 00:29:52,457
Not how I remember it,
and I've got witnesses to back me up.

316
00:29:52,624 --> 00:29:54,667
Do you like being an Air Force captain? Huh?

317
00:29:54,834 --> 00:29:58,254
Think the United States wants to bring action
against an old man in a wheelchair?

318
00:29:58,421 --> 00:30:00,340
He was standing on TV.

319
00:30:00,507 --> 00:30:01,966
He wasn't even in a wheelchair.

320
00:30:02,133 --> 00:30:04,385
Periodically he is,
and when he shows up in court...

321
00:30:04,469 --> 00:30:06,554
...you better believe
he'll be in a wheelchair.

322
00:30:06,721 --> 00:30:09,224
You're an ambulance-chasing
piece of shit. All the same.

323
00:30:09,390 --> 00:30:13,436
Always on a high horse,
always trying to make me feel like I'm--

324
00:30:20,693 --> 00:30:22,237
Look, um...

325
00:30:22,403 --> 00:30:27,116
...I'm a lawyer, and this is what I do
all day, every day, so how about this?

326
00:30:27,283 --> 00:30:29,577
I won't fly jet planes.

327
00:30:29,744 --> 00:30:33,331
You stay out of court. Does that sound good?

328
00:30:37,836 --> 00:30:40,046
You know, guys like you...

329
00:30:40,839 --> 00:30:43,466
...you think you're so damn smart.

330
00:30:43,716 --> 00:30:46,845
And you think you don't have
to play straight with anybody.

331
00:30:47,637 --> 00:30:49,055
The wheel is gonna turn.

332
00:30:49,764 --> 00:30:51,683
It always does.

333
00:31:06,322 --> 00:31:09,909
"A lawyer you can trust," my ass.

334
00:31:11,160 --> 00:31:13,663
Thank you for your service.

335
00:33:24,794 --> 00:33:27,672
Three-thirty in the morning? Seriously?

336
00:33:29,048 --> 00:33:30,091
Can you get me that?

337
00:33:32,218 --> 00:33:33,928
I don't know.

338
00:33:39,434 --> 00:33:41,477
-It's a real thing?
-Yeah.

339
00:33:41,644 --> 00:33:43,563
Then yeah. I know someone who can get it.

340
00:33:43,730 --> 00:33:45,273
How much?

341
00:33:45,440 --> 00:33:47,150
What do I look like, RadioShack?

342
00:33:47,316 --> 00:33:50,278
It's gonna cost you whatever it costs me,
plus my end.

343
00:33:50,445 --> 00:33:51,738
Well, let's start with that.

344
00:33:52,405 --> 00:33:55,408
Normally, be about 500...

345
00:33:55,575 --> 00:33:59,746
...but seeing that this is
an after-hours house call...

346
00:33:59,912 --> 00:34:01,873
...let's make it a grand.

347
00:34:13,384 --> 00:34:15,219
Hey, how's the pup?

348
00:34:15,386 --> 00:34:17,221
Doing okay?

349
00:34:19,265 --> 00:34:22,435
-Yeah.
-She's not being left alone all day, is she?

350
00:34:22,602 --> 00:34:24,937
-She's got plenty of company.
-Good.

351
00:34:27,690 --> 00:34:30,401
Hey, this is gonna take me a few days, so...

352
00:34:30,568 --> 00:34:32,487
...I'll let you know.

353
00:34:32,653 --> 00:34:34,363
And next time...

354
00:34:34,530 --> 00:34:38,367
...let's try to make business happen
during business hours.

355
00:35:13,486 --> 00:35:15,029
Mm-hm.

356
00:35:15,822 --> 00:35:20,243
Well, this will certainly help
my Thursday PowerPoint.

357
00:35:21,077 --> 00:35:22,703
Excellent.

358
00:35:24,038 --> 00:35:26,749
That's a draft letter from Kevin
to the Arizona regulator.

359
00:35:26,916 --> 00:35:29,377
I know he likes the personal touch.

360
00:35:29,544 --> 00:35:31,420
He's gonna love it.

361
00:35:31,587 --> 00:35:33,965
I can't believe you did all of this
in three days.

362
00:35:35,716 --> 00:35:37,385
Am I reading this right?

363
00:35:37,552 --> 00:35:39,387
Did you get the rehearing moved up?

364
00:35:39,554 --> 00:35:43,599
Yeah. Those are three possible dates,
pending your and Kevin's schedule.

365
00:35:43,766 --> 00:35:45,601
The soonest I could get is the 4th.

366
00:35:45,768 --> 00:35:48,062
You moved it up almost three weeks.

367
00:35:48,229 --> 00:35:50,690
I'll give it another shot
and see if I can do better.

368
00:35:50,857 --> 00:35:52,859
Ha, ha! Are you kidding me?

369
00:35:53,025 --> 00:35:56,028
Kevin will be popping champagne.

370
00:35:56,821 --> 00:36:01,409
-I knew you were the right one for this.
-Well, I appreciate the opportunity.

371
00:36:01,576 --> 00:36:04,829
You should've heard how that arrogant jerk
spoke to me at the hearing.

372
00:36:04,996 --> 00:36:09,500
Right there in front of Kevin,
he accuses me of muddying the waters.

373
00:36:09,667 --> 00:36:12,837
Muddying the waters.

374
00:36:13,004 --> 00:36:16,132
I mean, he's the one
who can't even get the address right.

375
00:36:16,591 --> 00:36:18,426
Yeah. That's-- Wow!

376
00:36:18,593 --> 00:36:22,471
I know you have friends over at HHM,
and they sure talk a good game, but come on.

377
00:36:22,638 --> 00:36:27,476
Guys like that, when crunch time comes,
it's always someone else's fault.

378
00:36:29,729 --> 00:36:30,771
Paige?

379
00:36:31,272 --> 00:36:33,608
I'm sorry to interrupt. It's almost 11:30.

380
00:36:33,774 --> 00:36:35,985
Thanks, Greta. I'll be right up.

381
00:36:36,277 --> 00:36:38,529
PAIGE:
So are we still on for lunch Tuesday?

382
00:36:38,696 --> 00:36:42,575
KIM: Absolutely, and, Paige,
thank you for everything.

383
00:36:42,742 --> 00:36:45,870
No. Thank you for cleaning up
that mess McGill left behind.

384
00:36:46,662 --> 00:36:49,957
Would you mind if I messenger that over
tomorrow morning, first thing?

385
00:36:50,124 --> 00:36:52,919
I'd like to take one last look
before we submit, just...

386
00:36:53,085 --> 00:36:54,670
...double-check a few things.

387
00:36:54,837 --> 00:36:55,922
Sure.

388
00:36:56,088 --> 00:36:57,548
So tomorrow, first thing?

389
00:36:57,715 --> 00:36:58,883
Absolutely.

390
00:36:59,050 --> 00:37:00,092
Thanks.

391
00:37:00,259 --> 00:37:01,761
-I'll see you, Paige.
-Okay, bye.

392
00:37:47,223 --> 00:37:48,683
How's it coming in there?

393
00:37:50,559 --> 00:37:51,894
Good.

394
00:37:57,441 --> 00:38:00,319
-Don't mean to rush you.
-No. It's okay.

395
00:38:04,907 --> 00:38:06,200
I'm done.

396
00:38:16,294 --> 00:38:17,753
Half a rainbow?

397
00:38:17,920 --> 00:38:20,131
Wanna keep going till you do the whole thing?

398
00:38:20,298 --> 00:38:23,426
No. If you're done, I'm done.

399
00:38:23,592 --> 00:38:26,595
You know, your clients seem
to like that rainbow.

400
00:38:26,762 --> 00:38:28,472
Think they're gonna miss it?

401
00:38:28,639 --> 00:38:30,474
Wait till they see what's going up next.

402
00:38:30,641 --> 00:38:32,685
They're gonna love it. You're gonna love it.

403
00:38:32,852 --> 00:38:34,437
Yeah? Should I be worried?

404
00:38:34,603 --> 00:38:36,147
Nope.

405
00:38:36,856 --> 00:38:39,275
What do you say
we get the hell out of here?

406
00:38:39,442 --> 00:38:41,360
Sounds good.

407
00:39:05,885 --> 00:39:07,178
You ready to hit it?

408
00:39:07,345 --> 00:39:10,056
Sorry. I just need to check one thing.

409
00:39:10,639 --> 00:39:13,267
It'll be two minutes. Tops.

410
00:39:38,376 --> 00:39:39,752
[KNOCKS ON DOOR]

411
00:39:45,758 --> 00:39:46,801
CHUCK:
Ernesto.

412
00:39:46,967 --> 00:39:48,511
ERNESTO:
Good morning, Mr. McGill.

413
00:39:49,053 --> 00:39:51,555
They didn't have Fuji apples,
so I got you Honeycrisp.

414
00:39:51,722 --> 00:39:54,183
-Hope that's all right.
-I'm sure it'll be fine.

415
00:39:54,350 --> 00:39:55,518
Did you get the, uh--?

416
00:39:55,684 --> 00:39:57,269
Yeah. I got them.

417
00:39:57,436 --> 00:40:01,482
I went ahead
and I figured I should maybe....

418
00:40:07,446 --> 00:40:09,532
I wrapped them up, you know? For safety.

419
00:40:09,698 --> 00:40:13,285
That's very thoughtful of you,
but I need them now, so....

420
00:40:13,577 --> 00:40:16,205
-You sure it's okay?
-It's okay.

421
00:40:21,627 --> 00:40:23,504
Ahem. Um....

422
00:40:24,547 --> 00:40:25,965
Yep.

423
00:40:34,557 --> 00:40:36,225
Perfect.

424
00:40:37,810 --> 00:40:39,353
[GROANING]

425
00:40:46,694 --> 00:40:48,237
Shit.

426
00:41:08,424 --> 00:41:09,717
Ah!

427
00:41:13,387 --> 00:41:15,347
Ernesto, could you come in here, please?

428
00:41:18,976 --> 00:41:21,312
Thought I could do this myself.

429
00:41:21,479 --> 00:41:23,272
Would you mind changing the batteries?

430
00:41:23,439 --> 00:41:25,483
Sure thing, Mr. McGill.

431
00:41:26,358 --> 00:41:28,068
Thanks.

432
00:41:34,617 --> 00:41:38,078
JIMMY [OVER RECORDER]:
<i>I changed 1261 to 1216. It was me.</i>

433
00:41:38,245 --> 00:41:39,997
Turn that off. Turn it off.

434
00:41:40,164 --> 00:41:42,791
-<i>It all went exactly--</i>
-Turn it off!

435
00:41:42,917 --> 00:41:43,751
Uh!

436
00:41:44,210 --> 00:41:46,629
You did not hear that!

437
00:41:51,383 --> 00:41:52,968
All right.

438
00:41:53,385 --> 00:41:55,596
Okay, Ernesto...

439
00:41:56,013 --> 00:41:58,641
...this is my fault, not yours.

440
00:41:58,807 --> 00:42:03,812
Um.... But now that you've heard it,
you need to understand something.

441
00:42:04,438 --> 00:42:07,316
You know about confidentiality, right?

442
00:42:07,483 --> 00:42:11,403
As employees of Hamlin Hamlin McGill,
you and I are both bound by the strictures...

443
00:42:11,570 --> 00:42:13,405
...of client confidentiality.

444
00:42:13,572 --> 00:42:16,242
By law. Both of us. By law.

445
00:42:16,408 --> 00:42:17,868
You understand what I'm saying?

446
00:42:18,035 --> 00:42:20,955
-So I'm not supposed to tell anyone?
-That's right.

447
00:42:21,121 --> 00:42:25,584
No matter who, no matter what reasons
you think you might have...

448
00:42:25,751 --> 00:42:28,921
...you must not-- You cannot tell anyone.

449
00:42:29,088 --> 00:42:31,507
There could be terrible consequences.

450
00:42:31,674 --> 00:42:34,635
Life-changing consequences.

451
00:42:35,761 --> 00:42:38,597
And we don't want you to get into trouble.

452
00:42:38,764 --> 00:42:41,183
If something were to happen to you
because of this...

453
00:42:41,350 --> 00:42:43,352
...I'd feel sick about it.

454
00:42:45,479 --> 00:42:47,022
Okay.

455
00:42:47,189 --> 00:42:48,357
Enough said.

456
00:42:49,233 --> 00:42:53,487
I guess I'll go finish
putting away the groceries. Okay?

457
00:42:53,654 --> 00:42:55,698
Thank you, Ernesto.

458
00:43:17,136 --> 00:43:18,929
[SIGHS]

459
00:43:28,022 --> 00:43:30,899
[♪♪♪]

460
00:43:54,381 --> 00:43:56,091
[DEVICE BEEPS]

461
00:46:08,348 --> 00:46:09,725
Hmm....

462
00:46:09,892 --> 00:46:13,437
MAN 1 [OVER RADIO]:<i> Tuesday,</i>
<i>high temperatures will be in the mid-60s...</i>

463
00:46:13,604 --> 00:46:16,023
...<i>with five- to 10-mile-per-hour winds...</i>

464
00:46:16,190 --> 00:46:19,359
...<i>but expect scattered showers Tuesday night</i>
<i>with lows in the 40s.</i>

465
00:46:19,526 --> 00:46:22,988
<i>Wednesday will be partly cloudy</i>
<i>with high temperatures in the mid-50s.</i>

466
00:46:23,155 --> 00:46:25,782
<i>The Grants area will have temperatures</i>
<i>in the mid-40s...</i>

467
00:46:25,949 --> 00:46:28,827
<i>...with southwest winds</i>
<i>15 to 20 miles per hour.</i>

468
00:46:28,994 --> 00:46:32,539
<i>Now let's get back to more</i>
<i>of your favorite sound: Souvenir Oldies...</i>

469
00:46:32,706 --> 00:46:36,919
...<i>with the Steve Ricketts Program</i>
<i>on KDSK, 92.7 FM.</i>

470
00:46:37,085 --> 00:46:41,548
MAN 2: <i>Thank you, Derek.</i>
<i>Love those temperatures. It's almost like--</i>

471
00:46:41,757 --> 00:46:44,927
[SONG PLAYING OVER STATIC]

472
00:47:06,907 --> 00:47:08,534
[TRANSMISSION STOPS]

473
00:48:53,180 --> 00:48:55,724
[SIGHS]

474
00:49:08,236 --> 00:49:11,365
[VEHICLE APPROACHES]

475
00:49:29,675 --> 00:49:32,386
[GAS CAP RATTLING]

476
00:49:44,856 --> 00:49:47,567
[♪♪♪]

477
00:49:55,325 --> 00:49:56,618
[DEVICE BEEPS]

478
00:50:15,345 --> 00:50:18,098
[♪♪♪]

